        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The molecular gas in NGC1266 is distributed in three main components, a compact, very dense molecular core, a molecular `disk', with a diameter of 1.5" and the molecular outflow which extends to a diameter of ~5" (Alatalo et al. 2011; see Fig 1). We thus propose here to observe this galaxy with 0.75" resolution, to match the beam to the bright molecular core, as well as to spatially resolve the outflow in many of the brighter lines. Due to the compact nature of the emission, we will be unlikely to resolve out any flux (and do not require the ACA). Having spatial resolution will also allow us to separate lines which arise only in the nucleus from those that may arise in the outflow.

Requested sensitivity:
NGC1266 has a flux of ~1 Jy/beam in 12CO(1-0), with a core line-width of ~120 km/s (and non-gaussian wings extending to ~400 km/s). Comparisons with line surveys of other systems (e.g. Martin et al. 2006, 2011, Snell et al. 2011) and models (e.g. Bayet et al. 2009, 2010, 2011) suggest that detecting lines with a flux around  5x10^-3 that of 12CO(1-0) allows access to many key diagnostic species, including those discussed in the science justification. In order to achieve 5 sigma detections of species at this level we thus require an RMS of ~1 mJy/beam in binned 20 km/s channels, in order to have at least 5 channels across the line. We can bin further in post-processing (achieving e.g. a sensitivity of 0.63 mJy/beam in 50 km/s channels) to get better S/N in weak lines, while still preserving a few channels across the line. We can also reduce the binning on bright lines in order to estimate the properties of the out-flowing gas in the line wings (which are detected even for dense gas tracers at IRAM, and should be easily mapped by ALMA).

Band 3 is ideal for our science goals, containing the ground state transitions of many molecules and isotopes. A sweep of the 3mm band at the requested sensitivity allows access to many key diagnostic species, such as C3H2, SiO, C2H, HNCO, HC3N, CH3CH, N2H+, etc, some of which have never before been detected in an early-type galaxy.  At these spectral resolutions (5-50 km/s) we will also be able to easily deal with the effects of line blending. Achieving similar sensitivities and spectral resolutions with other instruments would take much longer (e.g. ~50 hours with PdBI).

We have performed a simulation of this observation using the CASA package simobserve, using the CASSIS spectrum analysis package to generated a synthetic local thermodynamic equilibrium spectrum for an 8 GHz section of the band (using the molecular abundances of NGC 253). The spectrum was then scaled to match the observed flux of the HCN and HCO+ lines in NGC1266 (Fig 2), and input into simobserve (as a spherical 1.5" diameter source in a FITS cube). We ran the simulation for the requested angular resolution and noise level, and included the effect of atmospheric noise at a temperature of 270K. We detect a very large number of molecular transitions with excellent S/N (Figure 3). The abundances in NGC1266 are likely to be different, however this spectrum serves to illustrate that these observations will allow us to achieve the stated goals.


Correlator setup:
We request a spectral scan, allowing us to cover the ~85-112 GHz of the 3mm band with the wide bandwidth 1875MHz basebands and a raw resolution of ~3 km/s. We thus observe the most densely populated area of the band, with many lines of interest, while avoiding the very bright 12CO(1-0) line. The ALMA OT suggests that at the highest frequency requested we require ~12 minutes per tuning with the above setup. We would require 4 tunings, and thus our sensitivity request equates to a time estimate of ~2.2 hours.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
